state.meta: TAO defines "intermuscular bone" as part of the postcranial axial skeleton, but Grande and Grande 2008 describe "cranial intermuscular bones" with the following comment: "Gonorynchids possess a series of about fifteen rod-shaped intermuscular bones extending posteriorly from each epiotic. These bones were discussed in detail by PATTERSON & JOHNSON (1995) for Gonorynchus gonorynchus, and referred to as epioccipital fringes in GRANDE (1996). These cranial intermusculars were not observed in the holotype of †Judeichthys or in our specimens of †Charitosomus lineolatus, but none of our specimens has a clear view of the back of the skull. Nonetheless, in all other species examined, cranial intermusculars were observed. Therefore †Judeichtys and †C. lineolatus were coded with a question mark pending further study." (page 308)
